author: @TIGG22

text:
I see a lot of people doing the whole thing with referring to a 17 yo as a "child" and in my opinion doing more to alienate people from their argument than doing to curry support.  She was a minor at the time, not a "child".  People don't turn 18 and roll over from childhood to adulthood, there is more nuance to aging and maturing than that and acting like there isn't is harmful to the conversation. 

The laws exist in order to protect everyone regardless of individual maturity.  The law is black and white so as to protect everybody equally, and it's not the purpose of the law to be open to interpretation as such.  Was Cody wrong and unlawful in his behaviour?  Of course he was, but I don't want to be on the side of the argument that pretends that what he did was just as bad as it would be to SA a six year old child. 

Cody should be punished what he did, whether it be legally, or communally, people need to decide whether they want him to retain his platform; whether they believe or not that what he did was so immoral that he shouldn't be allowed to make a living online where he would have an impressionable and potentially vulnerable audience.  But regardless of the law being inherently black and white there are varying degrees of immorality, and I think that pretending that what he did was just as reprehensible as it would be to SA an actual child is just as harmful to the debate as it is to pretend that he did nothing wrong whatsoever.
